Choosing a Dataset

I knew that I wanted to create either an interactive Sankey diagram or create a geospatial visualization; I have always thought these types of visualizations were very interesting, do a good job of conveying a story, and Ive never created them before.

Finding an interesting dataset to make a visualization from was the longest part of the project for me (analysis paralysis). After spending a substantial amount of time on Kaggle, I decided between Netflix streaming statistics through the years, Titanic survivor statistics, and meteorite landing data.

When I explained my dilemma to my spouse (who works in the Space industry) she quickly settled it for me, meteorite landing data! With my decision made, I began evaluating the dataset.

Evaluating and Cleaning the Dataset

The dataset contained various pertinent information like the name of the meteorite, which was typically related to the city it was found in, the ID of the meteorite, the latitude/longitude coordinates of the discovery, the year of the landing, the mass of the meteorite, the classification of the meteorite (what type of composition did it have), and some other extraneous information like naming convention. The dataset originally had 10 columns, 45717 rows of data, and represents data from numerous countries.

The dataset did require a substantial amount of cleaning to be usable as they were numerous datapoints that were missing coordinates, NAN datapoints, contained invalid/incorrect latitude/longitude coordinates, and the sheer number of meteorite classifications could be overwhelming.

I decided to clean the data and focus on keeping the mass, coordinates, year of landing, and name. I cleaned the data by ensuring duplicate points were removed, only valid latitude/longitudes were present, and NANs were removed. In addition, I narrowed my range to more modern findings, from 1985 to the end of the dataset in 2013 and I sorted the data by year to see how the data changed through the years.

Upon completion of cleaning, the dataset was 10 columns with 23056 rows.

In[26]:
###Cleaning the data


#Getting rid of unhelpful data/NA's
df.dropna(subset = ['year', 'reclat', 'reclong', 'mass (g)'], inplace = True)

#Removing duplicates
df.drop_duplicates(subset = ['name', 'reclat', 'reclong'], inplace = True)

#Removing impossible latitude/longitude coordinates
df = df[df['reclat'].between(-90,90)]
df = df[df['reclong'].between(-180,180)]

#Removing a lot of erroneous (0, 0) location data points from the data
df = df[(df['reclat']) != 0 & (df['reclong'] != 0)]

#Changing year column to an integer
df['year'] = df['year'].round().astype(int)

#Focusing on modern years and removing infeasible dates
df = df[df['year'].between(1985,2025)]

#Sorting by Year
df = df.sort_values(by = 'year')

Goals/Preliminary Design:

To create an aesthetically pleasing data visualization that depicts the distribution of meteorite landings on a global scale To create a data visualization that can be easily interpreted by a wide audience of viewers. Non-technical adults should be able to easily understand what the visualization is presenting. Make it interactive and engaging (although I still didnt know what I was going for initially)

I started off with a brief concept that looked like a generic globe (land was green, water was blue, and impacts were dark blue).

I thought a globe with circles tied to the mass of the meteorite may provide a nice visualization.

I reviewed the design with a group of friends who work in AI/Data Science and the Space Industry and they thought the visualization was really interesting, however, there wasnt enough contrast in the color palette (too much green and blue). In addition, the globe was somewhat cumbersome to use as it doesnt show the Earth in one pane, so the user must constantly adjust the globe to see additional meteorite strikes. Lastly, they thought it was a good idea to provide differentiation between countries.

Final Design

Fortunately, its really easy to adjust these parameters in Plotly, so after playing with palettes, I decided on a SteelBlue color palette to emphasize color contrast, the winkel tripel projection to show the entire globe, and enabled country boundaries to improve granularity on landing sites.

Also, I added a play button to cycle through impact locations by year and a pause button to stop (which also aided in EDA, as I found data anomalies by stopping on years and evaluating the data). The viewer can also choose to select a certain year on the toggle bar to see a certain year.

Lastly, I added functionality around the data points themselves. If you hover over a datapoint, it will display some pertinent information about that collision; the size of the marker is also related to the mass of the asteroid to show where the largest meteorites were landing. The final data visualization looks like this:

In[28]:
###Creating the Visualization
map = px.scatter_geo(
    df,
    lat = 'reclat',
    lon = 'reclong',
    hover_name = 'name',
    hover_data = ['year', 'mass (g)'],
    animation_frame = 'year',
    projection = 'winkel tripel',
    title = 'Meteorite Landings by Year',
    size = 'mass (g)',
    color_continuous_scale = "Viridis",
    width = 1200,
    height = 800
)

map.update_layout(
    legend_title_text = 'Classification',
    sliders = [dict(
        active = 0,
        bgcolor = "LightGrey",
        borderwidth = 1.5,
        tickcolor = "black",
    )],
    geo = dict(
        showland = True,
        landcolor = "LightGrey",
        showocean = True,
        oceancolor = "SteelBlue",
        showlakes = True,
        lakecolor = "SteelBlue",
        showcountries = True,
        countrycolor = "white"
    ),
    updatemenus = [dict(type = "buttons", showactive = False,
                        buttons = [dict(label = "Play",
                                        method = "animate",
                                        args = [None, dict(frame = dict(duration = 1000, redraw = True), fromcurrent = True)]),
                                   dict(label = "Pause",
                                        method = "animate",
                                        args = [[None], dict(frame = dict(duration = 0, redraw = False), mode = "immediate")])])]
)

#Scaling marker size based on mass and setting a minimum so small meteorites don't get lost
sizeref = 2. * df['mass (g)'].max() / (15. ** 2)

map.update_traces(
    marker = dict(
        sizemode = "area",
        sizeref = sizeref,
        sizemin = 5
    )
)

map.show()

Conclusion

I got to show my Data Science/Space friends the final result and they appreciated the changes from the conceptual design.

This isnt without self-reflection; if I were to redo this design there are changes I would make. The first change would be improvements to the text formats. The title font could stick out more and I believe aesthetic improvements could be made to the toggle bar and play/pause buttons. In addition, I would improve the aesthetics of the data tab when you place your cursor over a location.

Despite those observations, I believe the visualization used contrast and color tastefully and provided a clear story regarding impact locations throughout the years.
